content: Well laid out, easy to use. Nice to be able to save info to the cloud. Would be nice if MRADs were added as a measurement and the Vortex EBR1 MRAD reticle.

Not being able to save input to cloud and/or not allowing users to transfer inputs to another device is a significant issue...phones don't last long and can die at the worst possible times. I am on my second or 3rd manual reentry. Hours will be spent on this as well as checking outputs. Still being told WebSync is coming back but it has been years. If you buy this write all your inputs down. Otherwise if your phone dies unexpectedly you have nothing. Frankly there are a lot of programs out there now and having recoverable inputs is a feature I would strongly recommend a new buyer consider. Other than that the program has been great.

replyContent: This was due to a server upgrade we were performing on the backend. This should be resolved as of today, please make sure you have the latest version of the app. If you have any further issues or need any assistance please email us at support@appliedballisticsllc.com and we will be happy to help. - Doc Beech.

We apologize for this, as we know it is not fun to rebuild profiles (we have to do it when we test the app changes). We added in many new features like Kestrel Elite, AB Connect™, WeatherFlow Meter and more.

content: Loved this app until I could no longer edit my loads or sync to my new phone after the old one died.

content: I used to love this app until they updated it. When they updated they took away key features that allowed every user to input their own information to acquire first hits. replyContent: The Segmented BC system was a temporary bandaid until we could finalize AB Connect™ and the live fire data off our laboratory. Instead of relying on an outdated system of BCs we provide doppler radar and live fire data as well as our own measurements of each projectile.

replyContent:
The app is organized into a hierarchy.  Rifle->Ammo->Environment->Solution.

So -- after adding a rifle, touch the rifle to open up ammo for that rifle.  You can then add pieces of ammo.  After you do that, you can touch the piece of ammo you are using and then you'll be able to enter environment data to calculate a solution.

Update november 2012. Have used the app a lot now on ANDROID platform, systematic bugs when working in metric, using DA as input and having subzero  temperatures. WHat happens is a HUGE discrepance between the "Single shot/ Trajectory" calculation (correct) vs the calculation done by HUD range steps (way off). See below for examples of actual calculations with DA minus 1600 meters and airtemperature minus 20 Celsius. Working with plus DA and plus temperatures seems to be no problem.  DA-1600m, airtemperature -20C  RANGE - SINGLE SHOT RESULT - HUD SCROLL RESULT (0.1 MRAD clicks) 1000m - 165 - 205  900m - 130 - 161  800m - 101 -122 700m - 77 - 91 600m - 57 - 65 500m - 41 - 45 400m - 27 -29 300m - 15 - 16

Impeccable precision, unique features, the only app to support "minor" ballistic factors (gyroscopic drift, coriolis, zeroing parallax),  simple use, clear output. There are however a few minor bugs / missing features that make it miss perfection by a few mils.  In particular: * no possiblity to export the resulting tables or graphs (e.g. send by email) * due to a bug in the reticle view of the trajectory calculations, the drop marks at reticle subtensions are wrong -- the zeroing distance is ignored (all metric, mils, zero at 300m) * sight height is in inches only (even though I set everything to metric; can divide by 2.54, but still annoying) * little choice of reticles (usmc mildot, gen 2 mildot, my favourite s&b p4l would be nice) * magnification settings and controls are a bit misleading for front focal scopes  But all in all, this remains the best ballistic calc for android out there, well worth the money.
